<p> <img src=3D"https://math.mit.edu/~djk/18_01/chapter17/equations/section=
03_eq01.gif" width=3D"345" height=3D"50" align=3D"absmiddle">=20
</p>
<p>Introduction</p>
<p><b>Introduction</b></p>
<p>The method of washers involves slicing the figure into washer&nbsp;shape=
d slices=20
  and integrating over these. It is highlyappropriate for computing the vol=
ume=20
  of a torus.</p>
<p><b>Rotate the circle</b></p>
<p>By rotating the circle around the y-axis, we&nbsp;&nbsp;generate a solid=
 of revolution=20
  called a torus whose&nbsp;volume can be calculated using the washer metho=
d.</p>
<p><b>Washer method</b></p>
<p>We revolve around the y-axis a thin horizontal strip of height dy and wi=
dth=20
  R - r.</p>
<p>This generates a disk with a hole in it (a washer) whose volume is dV.</=
p>
<p align=3D"center"> <img src=3D"https://math.mit.edu/~djk/18_01/chapter17/=
equations/section03_eq02.gif" width=3D"288" height=3D"61" align=3D"absmiddl=
e">=20
</p>
<p align=3D"center">R =3D right hand "x" value of the circle =3D <img src=
=3D"https://math.mit.edu/~djk/18_01/chapter17/equations/section03_eq03.gif"=
 width=3D"70" height=3D"32" align=3D"absmiddle">=20
</p>
<p align=3D"center">r =3D right hand "x" value of the circle =3D <img src=
=3D"https://math.mit.edu/~djk/18_01/chapter17/equations/section03_eq04.gif"=
 width=3D"74" height=3D"32" align=3D"absmiddle">=20
</p>
<p align=3D"center"> <img src=3D"https://math.mit.edu/~djk/18_01/chapter17/=
equations/section03_eq05.gif" width=3D"297" height=3D"132" align=3D"absmidd=
le">=20
</p>
<p><b>Volume of the torus</b></p>
<p>We get the volume of the torus by filling it with a very large number of=
 very=20
  thin washers, that is by integrating dV from y =3D -1 to y =3D 1.</p>
<p align=3D"center"> <img src=3D"https://math.mit.edu/~djk/18_01/chapter17/=
equations/section03_eq06.gif" width=3D"262" height=3D"181" align=3D"absmidd=
le">=20
</p>

